{"key":"post-16271746","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16271746</id>\n<content>I wouldn't go with 15 psi unless you have a ton of money to spend.&amp;nbsp; Also, 100,000 BTU won't touch a retort that size, as it would take forever to heat up.&amp;nbsp; I built the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Wood-Fired-Steam-Boiler&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;wood fired steam boiler&lt;/a&gt; pictured below last year.&amp;nbsp; We use it to sterilize up to 100 five pound supplemented sawdust substrate blocks daily, plus it provides steam to a heat exchanger in the intake air duct of our below ground &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Mountain-Mushroom-Farm&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;mushroom farm&lt;/a&gt;, to preheat the air 24/7 during the winter, and during the daytime all summer to provide a day/night temperature differential.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The first link above gives some construction pictures and text, but I apologize that the page isn't fully finished.&amp;nbsp; We're into our busy construction season again, so it won't have all the pictures up until this winter when I have more time for computer stuff.&amp;nbsp; The boiler operates at 1 to 1.5 psi which is enough to heat our farm and sterilize substrates.&amp;nbsp; We use an 8 hour sterilization cycle in our autoclaves, which are made from 55 gallon drums.&amp;nbsp; We have four of them now, like the one pictured below.&amp;nbsp; There's a lot more pictures in my gallery if you want to take a stroll.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/11-14/250136916-Boiler_and_loaded_sterilizer.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/11-14/250136916-thumb_Boiler_